🧠 First principle (don’t skip this)
Source files (.cpp) → must be listed → compiled
Header files (.h/.hpp) → optional to list → only for IDE visibility

CMake does not need headers to build, but you often include them anyway.

🧱 Method 1 — Directly list multiple source files (baseline)

This is the simplest and most correct starting point.

add_executable(MyProj
    main.cpp
    foo.cpp
    bar.cpp
)

👉 This is:

explicit
predictable
recommended for small/medium projects
Adding headers (optional)
add_executable(MyProj
    main.cpp
    foo.cpp
    foo.hpp
)

👉 This:

does NOT affect compilation
just helps IDEs (CLion, VSCode, etc.)
🧱 Method 2 — Split sources using variables
set(SOURCES
    main.cpp
    foo.cpp
)

add_executable(MyProj ${SOURCES})

👉 Why use this?

cleaner when the list gets long
reusable across targets

⚠️ Limitation:

still manual listing
variables don’t add real structure
🧱 Method 3 — target_sources() (modern, scalable)

Instead of stuffing everything into add_executable, you attach sources later:

add_executable(MyProj)

target_sources(MyProj
    PRIVATE
        main.cpp
        foo.cpp
)

👉 Why this is powerful:

lets you incrementally build targets
useful when splitting across multiple CMake files
🧱 Method 4 — Folder-based using file(GLOB ...) ⚠️
file(GLOB SOURCES "src/*.cpp")

add_executable(MyProj ${SOURCES})

👉 This auto-includes all .cpp files in a folder.
